both. Examining labor immigration policies in over forty countries, as well as policy drivers in major migrant-receiving and migrant-sending states, Martin Ruhs finds that there are trade-offs in the policies of high-income countries between openness to admitting migrant workers and some of the rights granted to migrants after admission. Insisting on greater equality of rights for migrant workers can come at the price of more restrictive admission policies, especially for lower-skilled workers. Ruhs advocates the liberalization of international labor migration through temporary migration programs that protect a universal set of core rights and account for the interests of nation-states by restricting a few specific rights that create net costs for receiving countries. The Price of Rights analyzes how high-income countries restrict the rights of migrant workers as part of their labor immigration policies and discusses the implications for global debates about regulating labor migration and protecting migrants. It comprehensively looks at the tensions between human rights and citizenship rights, the agency and interests of migrants and states, and the determinants and ethics of labor immigration policy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aEmigration and immigration law. 0aEmigration and immigrationxEconomic aspects. 0aEmigration and immigrationxGovernment policy. 0aForeign workersxCivil rights. 0aForeign workersxLegal status, laws, etc. 0aHuman rights. 0aLabor laws and legislation. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Economy.2bisacsh  aConvention on Migrant Workers.  acitizenship rights.  aeconomic efficiency.  aequal rights.  aethics.  ahigh-income countries.  ahigher-skilled workers.  ahuman development.  ahuman rights.  ainternational labor migration.  ainternational migrant rights.  